Tree growing

  • Divide the predictor space into \(J\) disjoint regions, or boxes, \(R_1,\dots,R_J\). These boxes must minimize the RSS given by

\[ \sum_{j=1}^J\sum_{i\in R_j}(y_i-\hat{y}_{R_j})^2 \] where \(\hat{y}_{R_j}\) is the mean response for the observations in \(j\)th box.

  • The first split
    • for any \(j\) and \(s\), define pair of half-planes \[ R_1(j,s)=\{X|X_j<s\} ~~\text{and}~~ R_2(j,s)=\{X|X_j\geq s\} \] and we seek the value of \(j\) and \(s\) that minimize the equation \[ \sum_{i:x_i\in R_1(j,s)}(y_i-\hat{y}_{R_1})^2 + \sum_{i:x_i\in R_2(j,s)}(y_i-\hat{y}_{R_2})^2 \] where \(\hat{y}_{R_1}\) and \(\hat{y}_{R_2}\) are mean response in \(R_1(j,s)\) and \(R_2(j,s)\) respectively. (Note: in this step, finding the values of \(j\) and \(s\) that minimize the above objective function can be done quite quickly when \(p\) is not too large.)
  • The second split
    • Instetad of splitting the entire predictor space, we split one of the two previously identified regions. We know have three regions.
  • The third split
    • Again, we look to split one of these three regions further, so as to minimize the RSS within each region.

  • Keep doing until a stopping criterion is reached; for instance, we may continue until no region contains more than five observations.

  • A full growing tree may produce good predictions on the training set, but it is also likely to overfit the data.

Tree pruning

  • A good strategy is to grow a very large tree \(T_0\), and then prune it back in order to obtain a subtree.

  • Idea: regularization, put an \(l_0\) penalty on the number of node

  • For each value of \(\alpha\) there corresponds a subtree \(T\subset T_0\) such that \[ \sum_{m=1}^{|T|}\sum_{i:x_i\in R_m}(y_i-\hat{y}_{R_m})^2 + \alpha|T| \] is as small as possible. Here \(|T|\) indicates the number of terminal nodes of the tree \(T\)

  • As we increase \(\alpha\) from zero, branches get pruned from the tree in a nested and predictable fashion, so obtaining the whole sequence of subtrees as a function of \(\alpha\) is easy.

  • \(\alpha\) can be selected by K fold CV.

Bagging and Random forest

  • If we focus on the prediction performance, without any caring about interpretation, what can we do furhter ?
    • We can grow our tree as large as possible to improve the ability in prediction. However, this large tree suffers from high variance.
    • Bagging, random forest and Boosting
  • Basic idea of bagging: given \(n\) independent observations \(Z_1,\dots,Z_n\), each with variance \(\sigma^2\), the variance of the mean \(\bar{Z}\) of the observations is given by \(\sigma^2/n\)
  • Extend this idear to regression tree:
    • Obtain \(B\) bootstrap sample from training set
    • Calculate \(\hat{f}^1(x), \dots, \hat{f}^B(x)\) using \(B\) separate training sets.
    • Average them \[ \hat{f}_{\text{avg}}(x) = \frac{1}{B}\sum_{b=1}^B\hat{f}^b(x) \]

Bagging and random forest

  • Note that there are two problems in bagging
    1. Suppose there is one strong covariate affect response mostly, the strong covariates is believed to exist consistently and be used in the top split in each bootstrap sample. It leads to similar structure among different bootstraped trees and will not significantly reduce prediction error.
    2. After finishing bagging, how to evaluate prediction error ?
  • To solve 1., in each bootstrap sample, fit tree with a random sample of \(m\) predictors (\(m\approx \sqrt{p}\))
    • The algorithm decorrelates the bagged trees
    • On average \(\frac{{p-1 \choose m}}{{p \choose m}} = 1-\frac{m}{p}\) of bootstraped trees will not even consider ther strong predictor.

  • To solve 2., there is a trick to calcute prediction error: out-of-bag error estimation

    • Given data \(x_1,\dots,x_n\), we take length \(n\) resampling (sample with replacement) from \(\{x\}\), denoted as \(S\), what is the probability of \(x_j\) does not exist in this sample \(S\)? \[ p(x_j\not\in S)=\frac{(n-1)^n}{n^n}=\left(1-\frac{1}{n}\right)^n, j=1,\dots,n \]

    • On average, each bagged tree makes use of around two-thirds of the observations. Therefore, we can use remaining one-third out-of-bag observations as testing data.

Classification tree

  • The story is same as in regression tree except the evaluation of error rate, we denote it as node impurity.

  • Given node \(\tau\), let \(\pi_j\) be the \(j_{th}\) class, \(j=1,\dots,K; K\geq 2\). The impurity function is defined as \[ i(\tau)=\phi(p(1|\tau),\dots,p(K|\tau)) \] where \(p(j|\tau)\) is an estimate of \(P(X\in\pi_j)\), the conditional probability that an observation \(X\) is in \(\pi_j\) given that it falls into node \(\tau\).

  • A good impurity function should satisfiy the following three properties:
    1. \(\phi\) is symmetric
    2. \(\phi\) is maximized at \((\frac{1}{K},\dots,\frac{1}{K})\)
    3. \(\phi\) is minimized at \((1,0,\dots,0), (0,1,\dots,0), (0,0,\dots,1)\)

Impurity functions

  • Misclassification rate \[ 1-\max_{j=1,\dots,K}p(j|\tau) \]
  • Entropy function \[ \phi(p(1|\tau),\dots,p(K|\tau))=-\sum_{j=1}^K p(j|\tau)\log p(j|\tau) \]
  • Gini function \[ \phi(p(1|\tau),\dots,p(K|\tau))=\sum_{j=1}^K p(j|\tau)(1-p(j|\tau)) \]

  • The goodness of split \(s\) at node \(\tau\) is given the reduction in impurity gained by splitting the parent node \(\tau\) into \(\tau_R\) and \(\tau_L\) \[ \triangle i(s,\tau) = i(\tau)-i(\tau_L)-i(\tau_R) \] The best split for the single variable \(X_j\) is the one that has largest value of \(\triangle i(s,\tau)\) over all \(s\in \mathcal{S}_j\)
